First, we note that the greatest common divisor (GCD) of 6, 10, and 15 is 1, which means there exists a largest non-makable number. We analyze the problem by considering the parity and modulo operations: - Even numbers can be formed using 6 and 10. - Odd numbers can be formed using 15 and combinations of 6 and 10. Since 14 cannot be formed by 6 and 10, it is a candidate. For odd numbers, the smallest is 15, so all odd numbers greater than or equal to 15 can be formed by adding 15 to combinations of 6 and 10.
